SIMPLE: inn
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inn
<hw>Inn</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>in</ets>,
<ets>inn</ets>, house, chamber, inn, from AS. <ets>in</ets> in; akin to
Icel. <ets>inni</ets> house. See <er>In</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
place of shelter; hence, dwelling; habitation; residence; abode.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Therefore with me ye may take up your <qex>inn</qex>⟦br⟧
For this same night.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A house for the lodging and entertainment of
travelers or wayfarers; a tavern; a public house; a hotel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ As distinguished from a private boarding house, an inn
is a house for the entertainment of all travelers of good conduct and
means of payment, as guests for a brief period, not as lodgers or
boarders by contract.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The miserable fare and miserable lodgment of a provincial
<qex>inn</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The town residence of a nobleman or distinguished
person; <as>as, Leicester <ex>Inn</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One of the colleges (societies or buildings) in
London, for students of the law barristers; <as>as, the <ex>Inns</ex> of
Court; the <ex>Inns</ex> of Chancery; Serjeants'
<ex>Inns</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Inns of chancery</b></col> <fld>(Eng.)</fld>,
<cd>colleges in which young students formerly began their law studies,
now occupied chiefly bp attorn`ys, solocitors, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Inns
of court</b></col> <fld>(Eng.)</fld>, <cd>the four societies of
⟦ldquo⟧students and practicers of the law of England⟦rdquo⟧ which in
London exercise the exclusive right of admitting persons to practice at
the bar; also, the buildings in which the law students and barristers
have their chambers. They are the Inner Temple, the Middle Temple,
Lincoln's Inn, and Gray's Inn.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 766 --></p>

<p><ent>Inn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inn
<hw>Inn</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Inned</conjf> <pr>(⟦icr⟧nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Inning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To take lodging; to
lodge.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Inn
<hw>Inn</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To house; to
lodge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he had brought them into his city⟦br⟧
And <qex>inned</qex> them, everich at his degree.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To get in; to in. See <er>In</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>innards</ent>⟦br⟧
